nd of [[ship's bells]], the group find themselves shipwrecked on a mysterious uncharted island from which they are unable to escape.\n[[File:Christina Hart Jared Martin The Fantastic Journey 1977.JPG|220px|thumb|[[Christina Hart]] as Gwenith, with Jared Martin as Varian, in \"An Act of Love\"]]\nThey encounter Varian ([[Jared Martin]]), initially disguised as an [[Arawak]] native, who is later revealed to be from the year 2230.  A 23rd-century pacifist, musician and healer, Varian explains to the travelers that, like he and many before them, they have been caught in a space/time continuum where people from the past, present, future and from other worlds are trapped, co-existing on the island in a series of \"Time Zones\".  The only way home can be found in a place called \"Evoland\", which lies \"far to the rising sun\".  (It was indicated in interviews of the time that Evoland was also the name of the island.) The only way to travel between Time Zones is via invisible gateways that instantaneously transport individuals or groups from one zone to another. In one episode \"Beyond The Mountain\" the group also encounters a second cloud, which has much the same effect, but which also splits up the group.\n\nAfter the [[television pilot|initial pilot]] story, a steady group of travelers forms around Varian as ''de facto'' leader, and the series then follows this group as they travel across the many Time Zones of the island to find Evoland. On their way, they encounter people from different planets and times who are also trapped on the island and who have adapted to their plight in different ways. The pilot initially suggested the historical past would be explored; however, the producers of the show rapidly adopted a consistently futuristic tone during the series following pressure from the network. They also dropped three characters after the pilot, as they wanted a more exotic group of travelers, hence the arrival of Liana and Willoway. Liana disappears from the last two episodes when Katie Saylor fell ill.\n\n==Cast==\n* Varian ([[Jared Martin]]): \"A man from the 23rd century possessing awesome powers\", Varian generally uses a kind of crystalline \"tuning fork\" device called the Sonic Energizer through which he focuses his thoughts into what is described as a sonic manipulation of matter.  The device is completely useless in anyone else's hands, and seems capable of a huge variety of tasks, from opening doors to disrupting electrical systems to large scale acts of destruction, as well as its apparently intended function as a diagnostic and healing device. Following the departure of Professor Paul Jordan at the end of the pilot film, Varian takes over as ''de facto'' leader to the travelers and adopts a parental role over Paul's teenage son, Scott (most notable in episodes such as \"An Act of Love\" and \"Turnabout\").\n* Scott Jordan ([[Ike Eisenmann]]): \"The 13-year-old son of a famous scientist\", Scott has an excellent knowledge of Earth history and events, but is still young and has much to learn.\n* Dr. Fred Walters ([[Carl Franklin]]): \"A young doctor just out of medical school\" whose impulsive and rather hot-headed nature acts as a counterpoint to the calm, pacifistic Varian.  A friend of Scott's father and the only other member of the group from the same time period, the athletic black physician takes the role of protective \"older brother\" with the young teen.\n* Liana ([[Katie Saylor]]): \"Daughter of an [[Atlantis|Atlantean]] father and an [[extraterrestrials in fiction|extraterrestrial]] mother\", the beautiful blonde Liana possessed greater than human physical strength (due to her mother being from a [[planet]] with a higher [[gravity]] than [[Earth]]) and powerful [[psychic phenomenon|psychic]] abilities (presumably due to her mixed heritage) which allow her to, among other things, [[telepathic|telepathically]] communicate with animals. Saylor left the show after the episode \"Turnabout\" due to illness. In the next episode \"Riddles\" the reason for her not being present with the group was given that she opted to stay a few days at Coriel to help the inhabitants work out their new government and would catch up with the group later.\n* Dr. Jonathan Willoway ([[Roddy McDowall]]): \"Rebel scientist from the 1960s\" who has a mastery of computers, robotics and scientific knowledge which is quite useful to the group. He is something of a never entirely trustworthy [[black sheep]], basically a cooler version of Doctor Smith from ''[[Lost in Space]]'' without the congenital cowardice, who often tends to do things for his own mysterious reasons. Over the course of the episodes, however, the black-clad Willoway comes to care about Scott and his fellow travelers and becomes more integrated into the group, although Fred makes no secret about still not trusting him which leads to a bickering [[Mr. Spock|Spock]]/[[Leonard McCoy|McCoy]]-style relationship between the two.\n* Sil-El (The Felix Team<ref>http://www.cult.tv/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=210:fantastic-journey&catid=37:series-formats&Itemid=27</ref>): Liana's companion and pet, a \"[[Bicolor cat|tuxedo cat]]\" with which she can communicate telepathically and who sometimes scouts ahead for her, acting as an extra set of eyes and ears.\n\n==Production==\n[[D. C. Fontana]] recalled that once the show had been commissioned, she and the producers had a very short period of time to develop and produce the show before filming commenced. Additional scenes were filmed and inserted into the pilot which introduces the Atlanteans who are the focus of Episode 2, but this new material also quickly moves off-screen the characters Paul, Eve and Jill (who were originally intended to be regulars), as the network wanted a more diverse group of travelers. Also, a subplot involving the travelers finding a 1940s Air Force pilot held prisoner by 16th century pirates was removed from the first episode.\n\nThe show benefited from a larger than normal amount of location filming, with familiar sites such as the Hollywood Hills, Zuma Beach, the Bonaventure Hotel in LA and Griffith Park Observatory all appearing in various episodes. The character Willoway was created specifically with [[Roddy McDowall]] in mind. Fortunately the actor was interested and took the role when approached.\n\nAlthough airing in a time when the nation's interest in the [[Bermuda Triangle]], [[UFO]]s and fantasy was at a height, the show failed to last beyond the ten episodes, having been scheduled as a mid-season replacement (following the failure of another fantasy series, ''[[Gemini Man (TV series)|Gemini Man]]'') against ''[[The Waltons]]'' and ''[[Welcome Back, Kotter]]'', both very popular family shows.  NBC ordered 12 episodes to follow the revised pilot, but production ended early when it was apparent that the ratings were low. The show was either pre-empted or its time-slot changed several times during its short run. By its tenth episode, its ratings had dropped, and it was cancelled. The script for an unproduced eleventh episode, \"Romulus\", was once available on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051129041526/http://www.snowcrest.net/fox/journey/index.html |title=The Fantastic Journey: The Internet 'Portal' |last=Vikki |first=Virtual |date=2003-04-06 |website= |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref> Within a few months of its abrupt ending, several of the production team would be producing the thematically similar ''[[Logan's Run (TV series)|Logan's Run]]'' for the Fall 1977 season.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table\n |background=\n |overall=\n |title=\n |titleR=<ref name=\"WGAW\">From the Writers Guild of America, West catalog: {{cite web |url=https://apps.wga.org/coveredprojects/default.aspx |title=Signatory Project Confirmation [search: \"Fantastic Journey\"] |publisher=Writers Guild of America, West |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"U.S.C.O.\" />\n<!-- |director=\n |writer= -->\n |airdate=\n |airdateR=<ref name=\"U.S.C.O.\">From the United States Copyright Office catalog: {{cite web |url=http://cocatalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?DB=local&PAGE=First |title=Public Catalog - Copyright Catalog (1978 to present) - Basic Search [search: \"Fantastic Journey\"] |publisher=United States Copyright Office |date= |accessdate=March 10, 2018}}</ref>\n |episodes=\n\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=1\n |Title=Atlantium\n |AltTitle=Pilot\", \"Vortex\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|2|3}}\n |ShortSummary=A party of scientists disappears into the Bermuda Triangle and becomes trapped on an island where past, present and future co-exist. After meeting 23rd century healer Varian and encountering 16th century privateers, the survivors begin their quest to return to their own time. All the while, they are being observed by a mysterious man from a futuristic city in the desert.\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=2\n |Title=Atlantium (Part 2)\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|2|10}}\n |ShortSummary=With many of the original party returned to their own time, Varian, Scott and Fred find themselves caught up in the machinations of a megalomaniacal \"brain in a box\" called The Source, which has enslaved the inhabitants of the city of Atlantium (actually the [[Westin Bonaventure Hotel]] in [[Los Angeles]]), built by the survivors of the original Atlantis and intends to use Scott's life force to regenerate itself. The trio are aided by dissident Atlantean, Liana, who reveals that she is half alien.\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=3\n |Title=Beyond the Mountain\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|2|17}}\n |ShortSummary=The travelers are separated by a red cloud which leaves Liana as the 'guest' of Jonathan Willoway, who is the master of a utopian community of golden-garbed [[androids]], and the others trapped in a dark swamp surrounded by shaggy, green-skinned humanoids. However, Willoway's intentions are less than honorable and he has no intention of letting Liana leave, while Fred's medical skills prove invaluable in discovering the truth.<ref name=\"JKM-BtM\">{{cite web |url=http://reflectionsonfilmandtelevision.blogspot.com/2007/10/cult-tv-flashback-35-fantastic-journey.html |title=Cult TV Flashback # 35: The Fantastic Journey: \"Beyond the Mountain\" |last=Muir |first=John Kenneth |date=October 11, 2007 |access-date=March 10, 2018}}</ref>\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=4\n |Title=Children of the Gods\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|2|24}}\n |ShortSummary=The travelers arrive in a new Time Zone and meet a young boy who has escaped from a community inhabited solely by children led by the bullying teenager Alpha.\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=5\n |Title=A Dream of Conquest\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|3|10}}\n |ShortSummary=An alien dictator, Tarant, is planning to invade other Time Zones and conquer the island. Willoway pretends to agree with him so that he can learn Tarant's secrets, especially as the true leader of this alien community is being slowly poisoned by the would-be dictator. Meanwhile, Liana takes pity on an abused furry creature called the Nefring. \n\n''Guest star'': [[John Saxon]]\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=6\n |Title=An Act of Love\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|3|24}}\n |ShortSummary=Varian, under the influence of a love drug, meets a woman named Gwenith from a religious community in a geologically unstable Time Zone.  His judgment impaired, Varian decides to leave the travelers to stay and marry her. He soon discovers that the community fanatically worships a volcano god called Vatticus, who demands human sacrifices.\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |Title=Funhouse\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|3|31}}\n |ShortSummary=Arriving at a strange, seemingly abandoned 20th century [[funfair]], the travelers become part of a game played by an ancient Greek [[Magician (fantasy)|sorcerer]] named Apollonius who, with the help of a female [[werewolf]], plans to possess Willoway's body so that he can escape his imprisonment.\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |Title=Turnabout\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|4|7}}\n |ShortSummary=The travelers encounter a city where the women are subservient to brutish male authority. The women mutiny and imprison the male travelers in a strange black void, and Liana appears to join their cause. \n\n''Guest star'': [[Joan Collins]]\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |Title=Riddles\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|4|21}}\n |ShortSummary=Guided to an old house by a mysterious mounted messenger, the travelers \u2013 minus Liana \u2013 quest for an object that will assist their search for Evoland, and a strange couple conjures illusions drawn from their deepest fears. \n\n''Note'': The interior of the old house is the famous set of the Stephens' house in the sitcom ''[[Bewitched]]''.{{cn|date=March 2018}}\n |LineColor=\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |Title=The Innocent Prey\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1977|6|16}}\n |ShortSummary=A prison craft from Earth's future crash lands in the Time Zone where the travelers are resting, releasing two prisoners, a convicted murderer and a thief, into a community of stranded humanoid aliens that does not comprehend violence or the concept of doors and locks. With a killer on the loose scheming to abscond with an orb that gives the aliens psychokinetic powers, Varian and the others must deal with him and protect the pacifists.\n\n''Guest stars'': [[Lew Ayres]], [[Cheryl Ladd]], [[Richard Jaeckel]], [[Nicholas Hammond]], and [[Gerald McRaney]]\n\n''Note'': The opening of this episode uses flying saucer footage from the opening of the 1967 series ''[[The Invaders]]'' as the saucer approaches Earth.<ref name=\"JKM-TIP\">{{cite web |url=https://johnkennethmuir.wordpress.com/2012/03/11/cult-tv-blogging-the-fantastic-journey-the-innocent-prey-june-6-1977/ |title=Cult TV Blogging: The Fantastic Journey: \"The Innocent Prey\" (June 6[sic], 1977) |last=Muir |first=John Kenneth |date=March 11, 2012 |access-date=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n |LineColor=\n}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0075503|The Fantastic Journey}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-fantastic-journey|The Fantastic Journey}}\n* {{Epguides|FantasticJourney|The Fantastic Journey}}\n* [http://www.johnkennethmuir.com/JohnKennethMuirsRetroTVFile_FantasticJourney.html John Kenneth Muir's Retro TV Files - Retrospective]\n* [http://www.xmoppet.org/tv/journey.html Episode guide with links to screen caps and images, plus a 1977 article]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fantastic Journey, The}}\n[[Category:1977 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1977 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:Bermuda Triangle in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Sony Pictures Television]]\n", "name_user": "SMcCandlish", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePremise:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fantastic_Journey"}
{"title_page": "Ched Towns", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{use Australian English|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Ched Towns''' (16 February 1951 \u2013 20 January 2000) was a vision-impaired Australian Paralympic athlete, triathlete and adventurer.\n\n== Personal ==\nTowns was born on 16 February 1951 in the Sydney suburb of [[Penrith, New South Wales|Penrith]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Schaeffer|first=Stephen|url=|title=Paralympian relished pursuit of adventure \u2013 obituary.|date=27 January 2000|work=The Australian|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He was diagnosed with [[retinitis pigmentosa]] at the age of nineteen and by twenty two suffered night blindness. He married Judy and they had two children \u2013 Kane and Carlee. His daughter was also diagnosed with retinitis pigmentosa.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ross|first=John|url=https://issuu.com/nepeannews/docs/nepeannews_16february2017/11|title=Cruel diagnosis for Ched Town\u2019s daughter Carlie|date=17 February 2017|work=Nepean News|access-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe worked as a therapist, mediator and motivational speaker.\n\n== Sporting career ==\nTowns played rugby league for the [[Penrith Panthers]] [[Jersey Flegg Cup]] team until deteriorating eyesight forced him to leave the sport. He then took up triathlon and in 1982 competed in the Nepean Triathlon with wife Judy on the front of a tandem bike. Towns competed in more than 200 triathlons including eight Ironman events. In 1991, he became the first Australian triathlete with a physical disability to compete in the [[Ironman World Championship|Hawaiian Ironman]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />  He developed a system whereby his wife, Judy, would swim alongside him and then he would ride a tandem bicycle. His children Kane and Carlee would also guide him in triathlons. He ran in the [[City2Surf (Sydney)]] several times.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article102046331|title=Sportsmaster Inspires blind athlete|date=27 August 1988|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|access-date=17 April 2020|location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia|page=11 (SECTION D)|via=Trove}}</ref>\n\nHe took up the javelin under the guidance of [[Alf Mitchell]], who won the men's javelin at the [[1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]] in [[Perth, Western Australia]].<ref name=\":3\" />At the [[1988 Summer Paralympics|1988 Seoul Paralympics]], he finished fifth in the Men's Javelin B2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/ched-towns|title=Ched Towns|last=|first=|date=|website=International Paralympic Committee|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Adventures ==\nIn 1993, he was part of the Blind Leading the Blind expedition,along with fellow vision-impaired Paralympian [[Russell Short]] and able-bodied athletes Stuart Andrews and Brian Lang. They kayaked across the [[Torres Strait]], from [[Cape York Peninsula|Cape York]] to [[Daru]], [[Papua New Guinea]], then walked the [[Kokoda Track]]. The journey is told through the 1995 documentary ''The Blind Leading The Blind'' and the 2004 book ''Blind leading the blind: a journey of vision across the Torres Strait and Kokoda track.''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Andrews|first=Stuart|title=Blind leading the blind: a journey of vision across the Torres Strait and Kokoda track|publisher=New Holland|year=2004|isbn=1741101794|location=French's Forest|pages=}}</ref> Towns named his labrador [[guide dog]] Kokoda in honour of the expedition.<ref name=\"austgeo\">{{cite magazine|title=Ched's spirit lives on|work=[[Australian Geographic]]|date=October\u2013December 2000|issue=60|page=22|first=Elizabeth|last=Ginis}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, it was reported that he successfully completed the world's first free-fall for a visually impaired person.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Oliver|first=Paul|date=September\u2013October 1992|title=From bee stings to triathlons, to skydiving and trekking in Nepal, Ched Townes has shown .. the sky's not the limit.|url=|journal=Triathlon Sports|volume=8|pages=22\u201324|via=}}</ref> He rode across the [[Simpson Desert]] with his son Kane on a mountain bike for the Paralympic Appeal.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Schaefer|first=Stephen|date=May\u2013June 2000|title=Don't tell me I can't: Ched Towns.|url=|journal=Triathlon Sports|volume=15|pages=10\u201312|via=}}</ref>\n\nTowns had long gdreamed of climbing [[Mount Everest]], the world's highest mountain. In 1999, with the assistance of two mountaineers he climbed [[Aoraki / Mount Cook]] and [[Fox Glacier]], in preparation for climbing the [[Mera Peak]], [[Nepal]], which was to prepare him to summit Everest.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/20000126/A46066-2000Jan25.html|title=Weather hampers recovery of body|work=[[The Age]]|date=26 January 2000|archive-url=https://webarchive.nla.gov.au/awa/20001027143147/http://www.theage.com.au/news/20000126/A46066-2000Jan25.html|archive-date=28 October 2000}}</ref> On 20 January 2000, he died of a suspected heart attack while climbing Mera Peak, assisted by [[Michael Groom (climber)|Michael Groom]].<ref name=\":0\" /><refname=\"austgeo\"/>\n\nTowns view of life was \"You want to get to the end of your days and don't want to be sitting there wishing you had done this or that because it is too late then. You have got to do it now while you're fit enough and you're healthy enough\".<ref name=\":2\" /> Towns story was immortalised in the video documentary ''The Moth Loves Doodie'\u2019.\n\n== Recognition ==\n\n* Ched Towns Reserve at [[Glenmore Park, New South Wales|Glenmore Park]]\n* 2000 \u2013 [[Australian Sports Medal]] for his involvement in a wide variety of sports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/973853|title=Ched Towns|last=|first=|date=|website=It's An Honour website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2016 \u2013 [[Triathlon Australia]] Legend<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.triathlon.org.au/About/Celebration_of_Champions/Legend_of_the_Sport_Award/2016_Legends.htm|title=2016 Legends|last=|first=|date=|website=Triathlon Australia website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Towns, Ched}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Australia]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1988 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Visually Impaired category Paralympic competitors]]\n[[Category:Australian male triathletes]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Australian Sports Medal]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Blind people from Australia]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{use Australian English|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Ched Towns''' (16 February 1951 \u2013 20 January 2000) was a vision-impaired Australian Paralympic athlete, triathlete and adventurer.\n\n== Personal ==\nTowns was born on 16 February 1951 in the Sydney suburb of [[Penrith, New South Wales|Penrith]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Schaeffer|first=Stephen|url=|title=Paralympian relished pursuit of adventure - obituary.|date=27 January 2000|work=The Australian|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He was diagnosed with [[retinitis pigmentosa]] at the age of nineteen and by twenty two suffered night blindness. He married Judy and they had two children - Kane and Carlee. His daughter was also diagnosed with retinitis pigmentosa.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ross|first=John|url=https://issuu.com/nepeannews/docs/nepeannews_16february2017/11|title=Cruel diagnosis for Ched Town\u2019s daughter Carlie|date=17 February 2017|work=Nepean News|access-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe worked as a therapist, mediator and motivational speaker.\n\n== Sporting career ==\nTowns played rugby league for the [[Penrith Panthers]] [[Jersey Flegg Cup]] team until deteriorating eyesight forced him to leave the sport. He then took up triathlon and in 1982 competed in the Nepean Triathlon with wife Judy on the front of a tandem bike. Towns competed in more than 200 triathlons including eight Ironman events. In 1991, he became the first Australian triathlete with a physical disability to compete in the [[Ironman World Championship|Hawaiian Ironman]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />  He developed a system whereby his wife, Judy, would swim alongside him and then he would ride a tandem bicycle. His children Kane and Carlee would also guide him in triathlons. He ran in the [[City2Surf (Sydney)]] several times. <ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article102046331|title=Sportsmaster Inspires blind athlete|date=27 August 1988|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|access-date=17 April 2020|location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia|page=11 (SECTION D)|via=Trove}}</ref>\n\nHe took up the javelin under the guidance of [[Alf Mitchell]], who won the men's javelin at the [[1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]] in [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth, Western Australia.]] <ref name=\":3\" />At the [[1988 Summer Paralympics|1988 Seoul Paralympics]], he finished fifth in the Men's Javelin B2. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/ched-towns|title=Ched Towns|last=|first=|date=|website=International Paralympic Committee|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Adventures ==\nIn 1993, he was part of the Blind Leading the Blind expedition. The expedition involved Towns and fellow vision impaired Paralympian [[Russell Short]] and able-bodied athletes Stuart Andrews and Brian Lang. The expedition involved kayaking across the [[Torres Strait]] - [[Cape York Peninsula|Cape York]] to [[Daru]], [[Papua New Guinea]] and walking the [[Kokoda Track|Kokoda Track.]] Towns completed both components of the expedition and the journey is told through the 1995 documentary ''The Blind Leading The Blind'' and the 2004 book ''Blind leading the blind : a journey of vision across the Torres Strait and Kokoda track.''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Andrews|first=Stuart|title=Blind leading the blind : a journey of vision across the Torres Strait and Kokoda track|publisher=New Holland|year=2004|isbn=1741101794|location=French's Forest|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, it was reported that he successfully completed the world's first free-fall for a visually impaired person.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Oliver|first=Paul|date=September\u2013October 1992|title=From bee stings to triathlons, to skydiving and trekking in Nepal, Ched Townes has shown .. the sky's not the limit.|url=|journal=Triathlon Sports|volume=8|pages=22-24|via=}}</ref> He rode across the [[Simpson Desert]] with his son Chad on a mountain bike for the Paralympic Appeal.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Schaefer|first=Stephen|date=May\u2013June 2000|title=Don't tell me I can't : Ched Towns.|url=|journal=Triathlon Sports|volume=15|pages=10-12|via=}}</ref>\n\nTowns had long gdreamed of climbing [[Mount Everest]], the world's highest mountain. In 1999, with the assistance of two mountaineers he climbed [[Aoraki / Mount Cook]] and [[Fox Glacier]], in preparation for climbing the [[Mera Peak]], [[Nepal]], which was to prepare him to summit Everest.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/20000126/A46066-2000Jan25.html|title=Weather hampers recovery of body|work=[[The Age]]|date=26 January 2000|archive-url=https://webarchive.nla.gov.au/awa/20001027143147/http://www.theage.com.au/news/20000126/A46066-2000Jan25.html|archive-date=28 October 2000}}</ref> On 20 January 2000, he died of a heart attack while climbing Mera Peak.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/angel-of-love-comforts-survivors-20030521-gdvqoz.html|title=Angel of love comforts survivors|work=[[The Age]]|date=21 May 2003|accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTowns view of life was \"You want to get to the end of your days and don't want to be sitting there wishing you had done this or that because it is too late then. You have got to do it now while you're fit enough and you're healthy enough\". <ref name=\":2\" /> Towns story was immortalised in the video documentary ''The Moth Loves Doodie'\u2019.\n\n== Recognition ==\n\n* Ched Towns Reserve at [[Glenmore Park, New South Wales|Glenmore Park]]\n* 2000 - [[Australian Sports Medal]] for his involvement in a wide variety of sports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/973853|title=Ched Towns|last=|first=|date=|website=It's An Honour website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2016 - [[Triathlon Australia]] Legend<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.triathlon.org.au/About/Celebration_of_Champions/Legend_of_the_Sport_Award/2016_Legends.htm|title=2016 Legends|last=|first=|date=|website=Triathlon Australia website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Towns, Ched}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Australia]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1988 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Visually Impaired category Paralympic competitors]]\n[[Category:Australian male triathletes]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Australian Sports Medal]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sydney]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Graham87", "label": "safe", "comment": "better ref re death, add a couple of other details from it; add blind people from Australia cat; misc. changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ched_Towns"}
{"title_page": "Bengali Wikipedia", "text_new": "{{short description|Edition of the free-content encyclopedia in Bengali language}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = {{Wiki favicon}} Bengali Wikipedia\n| screenshot = \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a7\u09be\u09a8 \u09aa\u09be\u09a4\u09be.png\n| screenshot_size    = 250px\n| logo = Wikipedia-logo-v2-bn.svg\n| logo_size        = 85%\n| collapsible      = yes\n| caption = The homepage of the Bengali Wikipedia.\n| url = [https://bn.wikipedia.org/ bn.wikipedia.org]\n| commercial = No\n| location = [[Dhaka]] & [[Kolkata]]\n| type = [[Internet encyclopedia project]]\n| language = [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n| registration = Optional\n| owner = [[Wikimedia Foundation]]\n| num_users = {{NUMBEROF|USERS|bn|N}}\n| launch_date = {{Start date and age|2004|01|27|df=yes}}\n| author =\n| current_status = online\n}}\n\nThe '''Bengali Wikipedia''' or '''Bangla Wikipedia''' ({{lang-bn| \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be}}) is the [[Bengali language]] edition of [[Wikipedia]], the free online encyclopedia. Launched on January 27, 2004, it surpassed 10,000 articles in October 2006, becoming the second South-Asian language to do so.<ref name=\"Nazmul\">{{cite web|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/tech/news/article_1206718.php/Bengali_Wikipedia_crosses_10000_articles|title=Bengali Wikipedia crosses 10,000 articles|last=Noronha|first=Frederick|date=September 30, 2006|work=[[Indo-Asian News Service]]|publisher=[[Monsters and Critics]]|access-date=25 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226084330/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/tech/news/article_1206718.php/Bengali_Wikipedia_crosses_10000_articles|archivedate=26 December 2013}}</ref> In {{Date}}, total article crossed [[Special:Statistics|{{NUMBEROF|ARTICLES|bn|N}}]] articles with {{NUMBEROF|ACTIVEUSERS|bn|N}} active editors per month.<ref>This prediction is based on <nowiki>{{NUMBEROF|ARTICLES|bn|N}}</nowiki> Wikipedia template that automatically updates article numbers. So this is not a permanent or fixed count. The number of articles shown here, change in real-time as soon as a new article is created or removed. Therefore, this is not a reliable source and the numbers shown here are subject to change without prior notice.</ref><ref name=DS-1>{{cite news|title=A decade of Bangla Wikipedia An open call|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/bytes/a-decade-of-bangla-wikipedia-an-open-call-15875|access-date=15 April 2014|newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)]]|date=March 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323090248/http://www.thedailystar.net/bytes/a-decade-of-bangla-wikipedia-an-open-call-15875|archivedate=23 March 2014}}</ref> In 2018, Bengali Wikipedia was viewed about 190 million times from all over the world.<ref name=\"Jugantor\">{{cite web |title=\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0 \u09e7\u09eb \u09ac\u099b\u09b0 |url=https://www.jugantor.com/todays-paper/it-world/138790/%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%82%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%89%E0%A6%87%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A1%E0%A6%BF%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A7%A7%E0%A7%AB-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%9B%E0%A6%B0 |website=Jugantor |accessdate=28 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"techshohor\">{{cite web |script-title=bn:\u09e7\u09ef \u0995\u09cb\u099f\u09bf\u09ac\u09be\u09b0 \u09a6\u09c7\u0996\u09be \u09b9\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u099b\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be |url=https://techshohor.com/138140/%E0%A7%A7%E0%A7%AF-%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8B%E0%A6%9F%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%A6%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%96%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%B9%E0%A7%9F%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%9B%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%82/ |website=Tech Shohor |language=bn |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref> On an average, the site was viewed over 500 thousand times a day.<ref name=\"techshohor\"/>\n\nAs of January 2019, Bengali Wikipedia is the only online free encyclopedia written in Bengali language. It is also one of the largest Bengali content related sites on the internet. The mobile version of Bengali Wikipedia was launched in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u098f\u09ac\u09be\u09b0 \u09ae\u09cb\u09ac\u09be\u0987\u09b2 \u09ab\u09cb\u09a8\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be |url=http://archive.prothom-alo.com/detail/date/2010-03-16/news/49176 |website=www.prothom-alo.com |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt also has a phonetic Latin alphabet to [[Bengali alphabet|Bengali script]] tool so Latin alphabet keyboards can be used to type Bengali without downloading any software. Community-produced news publications include ''WikiBarta''.\n\n==Early history==\nIn February 2002, the developers started creating language-code based sub-domains for different language Wikipedias. Along with other Wikipedia sub-domains, Bengali language sub-domain was created at that time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bn.wikipedia.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020222224618/http://bn.wikipedia.com/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2002-02-22|title=Wikipedia: HomePage|date=2002-02-22|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> A placeholder page was created automatically in that sub-domain on June 1, 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bn.wikipedia.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020723102052/http://bn.wikipedia.com/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2002-07-23|title=Wikipedia: HomePage|date=2002-07-23|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> On December 9, 2003, A Bangladeshi Ph.D. student of Canada's McGill University named Shah Asaduzzaman emailed Wikipedia Founder [[Jimmy Wales]] with a request to create Bengali Wikipedia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lists.gt.net/wiki/wikitech/11087|title=Mailing List Archive: [asad@cs.mcgill.ca: About starting a new wikipedia in language : Bengali]|website=lists.gt.net|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Kalerkantho\">{{cite web |title=\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae |url=http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467582 |website=Kalerkantho |accessdate=27 January 2019 |language=bn |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190128030422/http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467582 |archive-date=28 January 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> As a result, the developers created a test page on the Wikipedia named \"Home Page\" on December 26 of the same year.<ref name=\"Kalerkantho\"/>\n\nThe Main Page of Bengali Wikipedia was created on January 27, 2004 from an IP address which marks the official beginning of Bengali Wikipedia. '[[:bn:\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be|\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be]]' (\"B\u0101ngl\u0101 Bh\u0101sh\u0101\"; Bengali Language in English) is the first article of Bengali Wikipedia which was created on May 24, 2004.\n\n==History==\n[[File:10th year anniversary of Bengali Wikipedia.jpg|300px|thumb|Wikipedia founder [[Jimmy Wales]] with Bengali Wikipedians during Bengali Wikipedia's 10th anniversary celebration in [[Dhaka]] (2015).]]\nBengali Wikipedia started its journey in January 27, 2004.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467581|title=\u098f\u0995\u09a8\u099c\u09b0\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u2013 \u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09a3\u09cd\u09a0|first=Kaler|last=Kantho|publisher=|access-date=2018-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911191715/http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467581|archive-date=2018-09-11|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kalerkantho.com/print-edition/tech-everyday/2018/01/28/595065|title=\u09e7\u09ea \u09ac\u099b\u09b0\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u2013 \u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09a3\u09cd\u09a0|first=Kaler|last=Kantho|publisher=}}</ref> Back then, the people of Bangladesh had a little interest in Wikipedia. A few students and scholars used the [[English Wikipedia]], but it was not accountable. Besides that, there were various difficulties contributing in Bengali. The whole scenario has been changed in 2006.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467571|title=\u09af\u09c1\u0997 \u09aa\u09c7\u09b0\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u2013 \u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09a3\u09cd\u09a0|first=Kaler|last=Kantho|publisher=|access-date=2018-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911191623/http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467571|archive-date=2018-09-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> During that time, the Bengali blogging world was growing slowly, and many people became accustomed to Bengali computing where a [[free and open-source]] Bengali typing tool, [[Avro Keyboard]] played a key role. On March 25, 2006, a Wiki team was created by the \u2018Bangladesh Open Source Network\u2019 (BdOSN) to popularize Wikipedia throughout the country.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> The aim was to represent the country to the world through Wikipedia and build a complete encyclopedia in Bengali.\n\nAt that time, Bengali Wikipedia had only 500 articles. \u2018BdOSN wiki team\u2019 managed to spread the word through some newspapers and start a Bengali Wiki mailing list. Soon, many Bengali-speaking people from Bangladesh and abroad joined them in this dynamic project. As a result, by the end of the October, Bengali Wikipedia got to 10,000 articles.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Among the South Asian language Wikipedias, Bengali Wikipedia reached that milestone first, and many of these articles were illustrated with photos from the demonstrator of [[Bengali language movement|Bengali Language Movement]] Dr. Rafiqul Islam, who donated all his historical photographs taken during the language movement to [[Wikimedia Commons]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n{{Bengali Wikipedia article graph}}\nOne of the pioneer of the Bengali Wikipedia, Dr. Ragib Hasan said that {{quote|\u201cThe biggest challenge was writing something on internet in Bengali. The Bengali Unicode was not supported on most operating systems, only few websites on the internet supported Bengali Unicode, and users had difficulties configuring it. Moreover, the idea of writing something with Bengali Unicode was new. \u2026 in the beginning, the idea of a Wikipedia in Bengali was not actually workable.\u201d<ref name=\"auto1\"/>}}\n\nBetween 2009 and 2010, Bengali speakers from [[West Bengal]], India also started to contribute to Bengali Wikipedia.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> In the meantime, the [[Wikimedia Foundation]] started their operations and in October 3, 2011 a local chapter named [[Wikimedia Bangladesh]] was approved in Bangladesh<ref name=\"auto\"/> by the Foundation to promote educational content in Bengali. On February 26, 2015, Jimmy Wales, the co-founder of Wikipedia\u2014visited Bangladesh for a celebration program that was organized by [[Wikimedia Bangladesh]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.prothomalo.com/science-technology/news/59709/Wikipedia-co-founder-arrive-Dhaka|title=Wikipedia co-founder arrive Dhaka|website=Prothom Alo|language=en|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref name=\"prothomalo.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/technology/article/463339/%E0%A6%AF%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%A6%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%97%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%A8-%E0%A6%9C%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BF-%E0%A6%93%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%B8|title=\u09af\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09a4\u09be \u09a6\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u0997\u09c7\u09b2\u09c7\u09a8 \u099c\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf \u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b2\u09b8|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://somoynews.tv/pages/details/%E0%A6%A2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC-%E0%A6%89%E0%A6%87%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A1%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%B9-%E0%A6%AA%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B7%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A0%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%9C%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BF-%E0%A6%93%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%B8|title=\u09a2\u09be\u0995\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0 \u09b8\u09b9-\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09bf\u09b7\u09cd\u09a0\u09be\u09a4\u09be \u099c\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf \u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b2\u09b8|first=|last=webdesk@somoynews.tv|website=somoynews.tv}}</ref> to mark the tenth year of Bengali Wikipedia.<ref name=\"prothomalo.com\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thedhakatimes.com/58671/bengali-wikipedia-third-language/|title=\u0997\u09ad\u09c0\u09b0\u09a4\u09be\u09b0 \u09ac\u09bf\u099a\u09be\u09b0\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09a4\u09c3\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be \u2013 The Dhaka Times|first=The Dhaka|last=Times|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntvbd.com/tech/2524/\u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc-\u09a4\u09c3\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc-\u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be-\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be|title=\u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09a4\u09c3\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be|website=NTV Online|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/technology/article/460678|title=\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6\u09c7 \u0986\u09b8\u099b\u09c7\u09a8 \u099c\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf \u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b2\u09b8|website=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u0986\u09b2\u09cb|language=bn|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.ntvbd.com/sci-tech/1377/GP-subscribers-get-free-Wikipedia-access/print|title=GP subscribers get free Wikipedia access|website=NTV Online|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> In his keynote, Jimmy said that according to the article depth, Bengali Wikipedia is rated quite well.<ref name=\"prothomalo.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/technology/article/463339/%E0%A6%AF%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%A6%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%97%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%A8-%E0%A6%9C%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BF-%E0%A6%93%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%B8|title=\u09af\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09a4\u09be \u09a6\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u0997\u09c7\u09b2\u09c7\u09a8 \u099c\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf \u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b2\u09b8|website=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u0986\u09b2\u09cb|language=bn|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\nBengali Wikipedia now has {{NUMBEROF|ARTICLES|bn|N}} articles on various topics with {{NUMBEROF|ACTIVEUSERS|bn|N}} active editors per month. As of January 2019, Bengali Wikipedia is the only online free encyclopedia written in Bengali language.<ref name=\"Jugantor\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kalerkantho.com/feature/chakriache/2015/02/18/189075|title=\u099c\u09c7\u09a8\u09c7 \u09b0\u09be\u0996\u09c1\u09a8 {{!}} \u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09a3\u09cd\u09a0|website=Kalerkantho|language=bn|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> It is also one of the largest Bengali content related sites on the internet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kalerkantho.com/online/world/2010/02/19/33256|title={{!}} \u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09a3\u09cd\u09a0|website=Kalerkantho|language=bn|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n== Users and editors ==\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ '''Bengali Wikipedia statistics'''\n|-\n! Number of user accounts !! Number of articles !! Number of files !!Number of administrators\n|-\n| {{NUMBEROF|USERS|bn}} || {{NUMBEROF|ARTICLES|bn}} || {{NUMBEROF|FILES|bn}} || {{NUMBEROF|ADMINS|bn}}\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Confusion==\nOver the years, there have been confusion in [[Media of Bangladesh|Bangladeshi media]] regarding some information of Bengali Wikipedia. In April 2018, Bangladeshi print and electronic media reported that Wikipedia named [[Runa Laila]], a renowned singer from Bangladesh, among its Top 30 Bengali people of all time.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09b6\u09c0\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7 \u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09b6 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09a4\u09c7 \u09b0\u09c1\u09a8\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b2\u09be {{!}} \u0986\u09a8\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6 \u09ac\u09bf\u09a8\u09cb\u09a6\u09a8 |url=http://archive1.ittefaq.com.bd/print-edition/anondo-binodon/2018/04/05/268645.html |website=archive1.ittefaq.com.bd |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09b6\u09c0\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7 \u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09b6 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09b0 \u09a4\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u0995\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09b0\u09c1\u09a8\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b2\u09be |url=http://mzamin.com/article.php?mzamin=111375 |website=mzamin.com |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0 \u09b6\u09c0\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7 \u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09b6 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09b0 \u09a4\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u0995\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09b0\u09c1\u09a8\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b2\u09be |url=https://samakal.com/todays-print-edition/tp-entertainment/article/180438/%E0%A6%89%E0%A6%87%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A1%E0%A6%BF%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%80%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B7-%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B6-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%99%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BE%E0%A7%9F-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE |website=samakal.com |accessdate=17 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u09b6\u09c0\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7 \u09e9\u09e6 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09b0 \u09ae\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09c7 \u09b0\u09c1\u09a8\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b2\u09be |url=https://www.ekushey-tv.com/%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%80%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B7-%E0%A7%A9%E0%A7%A6-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%99%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%A7%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE/31423 |website=ekushey-tv.com |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> This confusion arises due to the use of a collage image in the [[Bengalis]] article's infobox at Bengali and English version of Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u09b0\u09c1\u09a8\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b2\u09be\u0995\u09c7 \u09a8\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u0997\u09a3\u09ae\u09be\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09ae\u09c7 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ad\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf |url=https://www.jagonews24.com/entertainment/news/418644 |website=jagonews24.com |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> In August of the same year, an unregistered user added fake date of death in [[Muhammed Zafar Iqbal]]'s article, which also attracted media attention.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u09a1. \u099c\u09be\u09ab\u09b0 \u0987\u0995\u09ac\u09be\u09b2\u0995\u09c7 \u09ae\u09c3\u09a4 \u09a6\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099b\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be |url=http://www.thebangladeshtoday.com/bangla/2018/08/03/%E0%A6%A1-%E0%A6%9C%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AB%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%87%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%AE%E0%A7%83%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%A6%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%96%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%9A%E0%A7%8D/ |website=thebangladeshtoday.com |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u099c\u09be\u09ab\u09b0 \u0987\u0995\u09ac\u09be\u09b2\u0995\u09c7 \u09ae\u09c3\u09a4 \u09a6\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099b\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be |url=https://www.jamuna.tv/news/44063 |website=Jamuna Television |accessdate=17 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u09ac\u09bf\u09b6\u09bf\u09b7\u09cd\u099f \u09b6\u09bf\u09b6\u09c1 \u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09bf\u0995 \u099c\u09be\u09ab\u09b0 \u0987\u0995\u09ac\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ae\u09c3\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09c1\u09b0 \u0996\u09ac\u09b0 \u09b8\u0982\u09b6\u09cb\u09a7\u09a8 \u0995\u09b0\u09b2\u09cb \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be |url=https://www.uttarbangergramunnayan.com/international-news/wikipedia-will-correct-the-death-of-zafar-iqbal/ |website=uttarbangergramunnayan.com |language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jamuna.tv/news/44085|title=\u099c\u09be\u09ab\u09b0 \u0987\u0995\u09ac\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ae\u09c3\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09c1\u09b0 \u0996\u09ac\u09b0 \u09b8\u0982\u09b6\u09cb\u09a7\u09a8 \u0995\u09b0\u09b2\u09cb \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be|last=Television|first=Jamuna|website=Jamuna Television|language=en|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{multiple image\n | align             = center\n | direction         =\n | background color  = #ffffff\n | total_width       = 1000\n | caption_align     = center\n | image1            = 14th Anniversary of Bengali Wikipedia, Dhaka 153.jpg\n | link1             = File:14th Anniversary of Bengali Wikipedia, Dhaka 153.jpg\n | caption1          = Bengali Wikipedia's 14th Anniversary group photo, Dhaka (2018)\n | image2            = 13th anniversary of Bangla Wikipedia with all wikipedians 02.jpg\n | link2             = File:13th anniversary of Bangla Wikipedia with all wikipedians 02.jpg\n | caption2          = Bengali Wikipedia's 13th Anniversary group photo, Dhaka (2017)\n | image3            = BNWIKI10-Bengali Wikipedians Celebration Group Photo-Wikipedia 10th Anniversary Celebration.jpg\n | link3             = File:BNWIKI10-Bengali Wikipedians Celebration Group Photo-Wikipedia 10th Anniversary Celebration.jpg\n | caption3          = Bengali Wikipedia's 10th Anniversary group photo, Kolkata (2015)\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[History of Wikipedia]]\n* [[Reliability of Wikipedia]]\n* [[Wikipedia community]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://bn.wikipedia.org Bengali Wikipedia] <!-- This is useful for mirrors of Wikipedia content -->\n* [http://bn.m.wikipedia.org Bengali Wikipedia mobile]\n\n{{Wikipedia}}\n{{Wikipedias}}\n\n[[Category:2004 establishments in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Wikipedias by language]]\n[[Category:Bengali encyclopedias]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi encyclopedias]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Edition of the free-content encyclopedia in Bengali language}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = {{Wiki favicon}} Bengali Wikipedia\n| screenshot = \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a7\u09be\u09a8 \u09aa\u09be\u09a4\u09be.png\n| screenshot_size    = 250px\n| logo = Wikipedia-logo-v2-bn.svg\n| logo_size        = 85%\n| collapsible      = yes\n| caption = The homepage of the Bengali Wikipedia.\n| url = [https://bn.wikipedia.org/ bn.wikipedia.org]\n| commercial = No\n| location = [[Dhaka]] & [[Kolkata]]\n| type = [[Internet encyclopedia project]]\n| language = [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n| registration = Optional\n| owner = [[Wikimedia Foundation]]\n| num_users = {{NUMBEROF|USERS|bn|N}}\n| launch_date = {{Start date and age|2004|01|27|df=yes}}\n| author =\n| current_status = online\n}}\n\nThe '''Bengali Wikipedia''' or '''Bangla Wikipedia''' ({{lang-bn| \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be}}) is the [[Bengali language]] edition of [[Wikipedia]], the free online encyclopedia. Launched on January 27, 2004, it surpassed 10,000 articles in October 2006, becoming the second South-Asian language to do so.<ref name=\"Nazmul\">{{cite web|url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/tech/news/article_1206718.php/Bengali_Wikipedia_crosses_10000_articles|title=Bengali Wikipedia crosses 10,000 articles|last=Noronha|first=Frederick|date=September 30, 2006|work=[[Indo-Asian News Service]]|publisher=[[Monsters and Critics]]|access-date=25 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226084330/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/tech/news/article_1206718.php/Bengali_Wikipedia_crosses_10000_articles|archivedate=26 December 2013}}</ref> In {{Date}}, total article crossed [[Special:Statistics|{{NUMBEROF|ARTICLES|bn|N}}]] articles with {{NUMBEROF|ACTIVEUSERS|bn|N}} active editors per month.<ref>This prediction is based on <nowiki>{{NUMBEROF|ARTICLES|bn|N}}</nowiki> Wikipedia template that automatically updates article numbers. So this is not a permanent or fixed count. The number of articles shown here, change in real-time as soon as a new article is created or removed. Therefore, this is not a reliable source and the numbers shown here are subject to change without prior notice.</ref><ref name=DS-1>{{cite news|title=A decade of Bangla Wikipedia An open call|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/bytes/a-decade-of-bangla-wikipedia-an-open-call-15875|access-date=15 April 2014|newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)]]|date=March 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323090248/http://www.thedailystar.net/bytes/a-decade-of-bangla-wikipedia-an-open-call-15875|archivedate=23 March 2014}}</ref> In 2018, Bengali Wikipedia was viewed about 190 million times from all over the world.<ref name=\"Jugantor\">{{cite web |title=\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0 \u09e7\u09eb \u09ac\u099b\u09b0 |url=https://www.jugantor.com/todays-paper/it-world/138790/%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%82%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%89%E0%A6%87%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A1%E0%A6%BF%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A7%A7%E0%A7%AB-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%9B%E0%A6%B0 |website=Jugantor |accessdate=28 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"techshohor\">{{cite web |script-title=bn:\u09e7\u09ef \u0995\u09cb\u099f\u09bf\u09ac\u09be\u09b0 \u09a6\u09c7\u0996\u09be \u09b9\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u099b\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be |url=https://techshohor.com/138140/%E0%A7%A7%E0%A7%AF-%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%8B%E0%A6%9F%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%A6%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%96%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%B9%E0%A7%9F%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%9B%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%82/ |website=Tech Shohor |language=bn |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref> On an average, the site was viewed over 500 thousand times a day.<ref name=\"techshohor\"/>\n\nAs of January 2019, Bengali Wikipedia is the only online free encyclopedia written in Bengali language. It is also one of the largest Bengali content related sites on the internet. The mobile version of Bengali Wikipedia was launched in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u098f\u09ac\u09be\u09b0 \u09ae\u09cb\u09ac\u09be\u0987\u09b2 \u09ab\u09cb\u09a8\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be |url=http://archive.prothom-alo.com/detail/date/2010-03-16/news/49176 |website=www.prothom-alo.com |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt also has a phonetic Latin alphabet to [[Bengali alphabet|Bengali script]] tool so Latin alphabet keyboards can be used to type Bengali without downloading any software. Community-produced news publications include ''WikiBarta''.\n\n==Early history==\nIn February 2002, the developers started creating language-code based sub-domains for different language Wikipedias. Along with other Wikipedia sub-domains, Bengali language sub-domain was created at that time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bn.wikipedia.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020222224618/http://bn.wikipedia.com/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2002-02-22|title=Wikipedia: HomePage|date=2002-02-22|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> A placeholder page was created automatically in that sub-domain on June 1, 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bn.wikipedia.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020723102052/http://bn.wikipedia.com/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2002-07-23|title=Wikipedia: HomePage|date=2002-07-23|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> On December 9, 2003, A Bangladeshi Ph.D. student of Canada's McGill University named Shah Asaduzzaman emailed Wikipedia Founder [[Jimmy Wales]] with a request to create Bengali Wikipedia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lists.gt.net/wiki/wikitech/11087|title=Mailing List Archive: [asad@cs.mcgill.ca: About starting a new wikipedia in language : Bengali]|website=lists.gt.net|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Kalerkantho\">{{cite web |title=\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae |url=http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467582 |website=Kalerkantho |accessdate=27 January 2019 |language=bn |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190128030422/http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467582 |archive-date=28 January 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> As a result, the developers created a test page on the Wikipedia named \"Home Page\" on December 26 of the same year.<ref name=\"Kalerkantho\"/>\n\nThe Main Page of Bengali Wikipedia was created on January 27, 2004 from an IP address which marks the official beginning of Bengali Wikipedia. '[[:bn:\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be|\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be]]' (\"B\u0101ngl\u0101 Bh\u0101sh\u0101\"; Bengali Language in English) is the first article of Bengali Wikipedia which was created on May 24, 2004.\n\n==History==\n[[File:10th year anniversary of Bengali Wikipedia.jpg|300px|thumb|Wikipedia founder [[Jimmy Wales]] with Bengali Wikipedians during Bengali Wikipedia's 10th anniversary celebration in [[Dhaka]] (2015).]]\nBengali Wikipedia started its journey in January 27, 2004.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467581|title=\u098f\u0995\u09a8\u099c\u09b0\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u2013 \u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09a3\u09cd\u09a0|first=Kaler|last=Kantho|publisher=|access-date=2018-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911191715/http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467581|archive-date=2018-09-11|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kalerkantho.com/print-edition/tech-everyday/2018/01/28/595065|title=\u09e7\u09ea \u09ac\u099b\u09b0\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u2013 \u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09a3\u09cd\u09a0|first=Kaler|last=Kantho|publisher=}}</ref> Back then, the people of Bangladesh had a little interest in Wikipedia. A few students and scholars used the [[English Wikipedia]], but it was not accountable. Besides that, there were various difficulties contributing in Bengali. The whole scenario has been changed in 2006.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467571|title=\u09af\u09c1\u0997 \u09aa\u09c7\u09b0\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u2013 \u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09a3\u09cd\u09a0|first=Kaler|last=Kantho|publisher=|access-date=2018-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911191623/http://www.kalerkantho.com/online/techbishwa/2017/02/25/467571|archive-date=2018-09-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> During that time, the Bengali blogging world was growing slowly, and many people became accustomed to Bengali computing where a [[free and open-source]] Bengali typing tool, [[Avro Keyboard]] played a key role. On March 25, 2006, a Wiki team was created by the \u2018Bangladesh Open Source Network\u2019 (BdOSN) to popularize Wikipedia throughout the country.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> The aim was to represent the country to the world through Wikipedia and build a complete encyclopedia in Bengali.\n\nAt that time, Bengali Wikipedia had only 500 articles. \u2018BdOSN wiki team\u2019 managed to spread the word through some newspapers and start a Bengali Wiki mailing list. Soon, many Bengali-speaking people from Bangladesh and abroad joined them in this dynamic project. As a result, by the end of the October, Bengali Wikipedia got to 10,000 articles.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Among the South Asian language Wikipedias, Bengali Wikipedia reached that milestone first, and many of these articles were illustrated with photos from the demonstrator of [[Bengali language movement|Bengali Language Movement]] Dr. Rafiqul Islam, who donated all his historical photographs taken during the language movement to [[Wikimedia Commons]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n{{Bengali Wikipedia article graph}}\nOne of the pioneer of the Bengali Wikipedia, Dr. Ragib Hasan said that {{quote|\u201cThe biggest challenge was writing something on internet in Bengali. The Bengali Unicode was not supported on most operating systems, only few websites on the internet supported Bengali Unicode, and users had difficulties configuring it. Moreover, the idea of writing something with Bengali Unicode was new. \u2026 in the beginning, the idea of a Wikipedia in Bengali was not actually workable.\u201d<ref name=\"auto1\"/>}}\n\nBetween 2009 and 2010, Bengali speakers from [[West Bengal]], India also started to contribute to Bengali Wikipedia.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> In the meantime, the [[Wikimedia Foundation]] started their operations and in October 3, 2011 a local chapter named [[Wikimedia Bangladesh]] was approved in Bangladesh<ref name=\"auto\"/> by the Foundation to promote educational content in Bengali. On February 26, 2015, Jimmy Wales, the co-founder of Wikipedia\u2014visited Bangladesh for a celebration program that was organized by [[Wikimedia Bangladesh]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.prothomalo.com/science-technology/news/59709/Wikipedia-co-founder-arrive-Dhaka|title=Wikipedia co-founder arrive Dhaka|website=Prothom Alo|language=en|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref name=\"prothomalo.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/technology/article/463339/%E0%A6%AF%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%A6%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%97%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%A8-%E0%A6%9C%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BF-%E0%A6%93%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%B8|title=\u09af\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09a4\u09be \u09a6\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u0997\u09c7\u09b2\u09c7\u09a8 \u099c\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf \u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b2\u09b8|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://somoynews.tv/pages/details/%E0%A6%A2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC-%E0%A6%89%E0%A6%87%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A1%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%B8%E0%A6%B9-%E0%A6%AA%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B7%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A0%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%9C%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BF-%E0%A6%93%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%B8|title=\u09a2\u09be\u0995\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0 \u09b8\u09b9-\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a4\u09bf\u09b7\u09cd\u09a0\u09be\u09a4\u09be \u099c\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf \u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b2\u09b8|first=|last=webdesk@somoynews.tv|website=somoynews.tv}}</ref> to mark the tenth year of Bengali Wikipedia.<ref name=\"prothomalo.com\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thedhakatimes.com/58671/bengali-wikipedia-third-language/|title=\u0997\u09ad\u09c0\u09b0\u09a4\u09be\u09b0 \u09ac\u09bf\u099a\u09be\u09b0\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09a4\u09c3\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be \u2013 The Dhaka Times|first=The Dhaka|last=Times|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntvbd.com/tech/2524/\u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc-\u09a4\u09c3\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc-\u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be-\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be|title=\u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09a4\u09c3\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09ad\u09be\u09b7\u09be \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be|website=NTV Online|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/technology/article/460678|title=\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6\u09c7 \u0986\u09b8\u099b\u09c7\u09a8 \u099c\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf \u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b2\u09b8|website=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u0986\u09b2\u09cb|language=bn|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.ntvbd.com/sci-tech/1377/GP-subscribers-get-free-Wikipedia-access/print|title=GP subscribers get free Wikipedia access|website=NTV Online|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> In his keynote, Jimmy said that according to the article depth, Bengali Wikipedia is rated quite well.<ref name=\"prothomalo.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/technology/article/463339/%E0%A6%AF%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%A6%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%97%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%A8-%E0%A6%9C%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%BF-%E0%A6%93%E0%A6%AF%E0%A6%BC%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%B8|title=\u09af\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09a4\u09be \u09a6\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u0997\u09c7\u09b2\u09c7\u09a8 \u099c\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf \u0993\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09b2\u09b8|website=\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u0986\u09b2\u09cb|language=bn|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\nBengali Wikipedia now has {{NUMBEROF|ARTICLES|bn|N}} articles on various topics with {{NUMBEROF|ACTIVEUSERS|bn|N}} active editors per month. As of January 2019, Bengali Wikipedia is the only online free encyclopedia written in Bengali language.<ref name=\"Jugantor\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kalerkantho.com/feature/chakriache/2015/02/18/189075|title=\u099c\u09c7\u09a8\u09c7 \u09b0\u09be\u0996\u09c1\u09a8 {{!}} \u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09a3\u09cd\u09a0|website=Kalerkantho|language=bn|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> It is also one of the largest Bengali content related sites on the internet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kalerkantho.com/online/world/2010/02/19/33256|title={{!}} \u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09a3\u09cd\u09a0|website=Kalerkantho|language=bn|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n== Users and editors ==\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ '''Bengali Wikipedia statistics'''\n|-\n! Number of user accounts !! Number of articles !! Number of files !!Number of administrators\n|-\n| {{NUMBEROF|USERS|bn}} || {{NUMBEROF|ARTICLES|bn}} || {{NUMBEROF|FILES|bn}} || {{NUMBEROF|ADMINS|bn}}\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Confusion==\nOver the years, there have been confusion in [[Media of Bangladesh|Bangladeshi media]] regarding some information of Bengali Wikipedia. In April 2018, Bangladeshi print and electronic media reported that Wikipedia named [[Runa Laila]], a renowned singer from Bangladesh, among its Top 30 Bengali people of all time.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09b6\u09c0\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7 \u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09b6 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09a4\u09c7 \u09b0\u09c1\u09a8\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b2\u09be {{!}} \u0986\u09a8\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6 \u09ac\u09bf\u09a8\u09cb\u09a6\u09a8 |url=http://archive1.ittefaq.com.bd/print-edition/anondo-binodon/2018/04/05/268645.html |website=archive1.ittefaq.com.bd |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09b6\u09c0\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7 \u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09b6 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09b0 \u09a4\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u0995\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09b0\u09c1\u09a8\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b2\u09be |url=http://mzamin.com/article.php?mzamin=111375 |website=mzamin.com |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be\u09b0 \u09b6\u09c0\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7 \u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09b6 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09b0 \u09a4\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u0995\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u09b0\u09c1\u09a8\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b2\u09be |url=https://samakal.com/todays-print-edition/tp-entertainment/article/180438/%E0%A6%89%E0%A6%87%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%AA%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A1%E0%A6%BF%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%80%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B7-%E0%A6%A4%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B0%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B6-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%99%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%A4%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%BE%E0%A7%9F-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE |website=samakal.com |accessdate=17 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u09b6\u09c0\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7 \u09e9\u09e6 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09b0 \u09ae\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09c7 \u09b0\u09c1\u09a8\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b2\u09be |url=https://www.ekushey-tv.com/%E0%A6%B6%E0%A7%80%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%B7-%E0%A7%A9%E0%A7%A6-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%99%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%AE%E0%A6%A7%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AF%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%81%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BE-%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE%E0%A7%9F%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%BE/31423 |website=ekushey-tv.com |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> This confusion arises due to the use of a collage image in the [[Bengalis]] article's infobox at Bengali and English version of Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u09b0\u09c1\u09a8\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b2\u09be\u0995\u09c7 \u09a8\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09c7 \u0997\u09a3\u09ae\u09be\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09ae\u09c7 \u09ac\u09bf\u09ad\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf |url=https://www.jagonews24.com/entertainment/news/418644 |website=jagonews24.com |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref> In August of the same year, an unregistered user added fake date of death in [[Muhammed Zafar Iqbal]]'s article, which also attracted media attention.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u09a1. \u099c\u09be\u09ab\u09b0 \u0987\u0995\u09ac\u09be\u09b2\u0995\u09c7 \u09ae\u09c3\u09a4 \u09a6\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099b\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be |url=http://www.thebangladeshtoday.com/bangla/2018/08/03/%E0%A6%A1-%E0%A6%9C%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%AB%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%87%E0%A6%95%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%95%E0%A7%87-%E0%A6%AE%E0%A7%83%E0%A6%A4-%E0%A6%A6%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%96%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%9A%E0%A7%8D/ |website=thebangladeshtoday.com |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u099c\u09be\u09ab\u09b0 \u0987\u0995\u09ac\u09be\u09b2\u0995\u09c7 \u09ae\u09c3\u09a4 \u09a6\u09c7\u0996\u09be\u099a\u09cd\u099b\u09c7 \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be |url=https://www.jamuna.tv/news/44063 |website=Jamuna Television |accessdate=17 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u099c\u09be\u09ab\u09b0 \u0987\u0995\u09ac\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ae\u09c3\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09c1\u09b0 \u0996\u09ac\u09b0 \u09b8\u0982\u09b6\u09cb\u09a7\u09a8 \u0995\u09b0\u09b2\u09cb \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be |url=https://www.jamunatv.online/news/9584 |website=jamunatv.online |accessdate=17 March 2019 }}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jamuna.tv/news/44085|title=\u099c\u09be\u09ab\u09b0 \u0987\u0995\u09ac\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ae\u09c3\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09c1\u09b0 \u0996\u09ac\u09b0 \u09b8\u0982\u09b6\u09cb\u09a7\u09a8 \u0995\u09b0\u09b2\u09cb \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u0989\u0987\u0995\u09bf\u09aa\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09be|last=Television|first=Jamuna|website=Jamuna Television|language=en|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{multiple image\n | align             = center\n | direction         =\n | background color  = #ffffff\n | total_width       = 1000\n | caption_align     = center\n | image1            = 14th Anniversary of Bengali Wikipedia, Dhaka 153.jpg\n | link1             = File:14th Anniversary of Bengali Wikipedia, Dhaka 153.jpg\n | caption1          = Bengali Wikipedia's 14th Anniversary group photo, Dhaka (2018)\n | image2            = 13th anniversary of Bangla Wikipedia with all wikipedians 02.jpg\n | link2             = File:13th anniversary of Bangla Wikipedia with all wikipedians 02.jpg\n | caption2          = Bengali Wikipedia's 13th Anniversary group photo, Dhaka (2017)\n | image3            = BNWIKI10-Bengali Wikipedians Celebration Group Photo-Wikipedia 10th Anniversary Celebration.jpg\n | link3             = File:BNWIKI10-Bengali Wikipedians Celebration Group Photo-Wikipedia 10th Anniversary Celebration.jpg\n | caption3          = Bengali Wikipedia's 10th Anniversary group photo, Kolkata (2015)\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[History of Wikipedia]]\n* [[Reliability of Wikipedia]]\n* [[Wikipedia community]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://bn.wikipedia.org Bengali Wikipedia] <!-- This is useful for mirrors of Wikipedia content -->\n* [http://bn.m.wikipedia.org Bengali Wikipedia mobile]\n\n{{Wikipedia}}\n{{Wikipedias}}\n\n[[Category:2004 establishments in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Wikipedias by language]]\n[[Category:Bengali encyclopedias]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi encyclopedias]]\n", "name_user": "01prasantaubg", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bengali_Wikipedia"}
