{"title_page": "Amos Foster", "text_new": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Amos Foster\n| image = Amos P. Foster.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Foster from 1907 ''Cornhusker''\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1880|3|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Keene, New Hampshire]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1952|8|7|1880|3|10}}\n| death_place = [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, Ohio]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_sport1 = Football\n| player_years2 = 1902\u20131903\n| player_team2 = [[Dartmouth Big Green football|Dartmouth]]\n| player_sport3 = Basketball\n| player_years4 = 1900\u20131903\n| player_team4 = [[Dartmouth Big Green men's basketball|Dartmouth]]\n| player_positions = [[Fullback (gridiron football)|Fullback]] (football)\n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1904\u20131905\n| coach_team2 = [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n| coach_years3 = 1906\n| coach_team3 = [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]]\n| coach_years4 = 1907\u20131908\n| coach_team4 = [[Miami RedHawks football|Miami (OH)]]\n| coach_sport5 = Basketball\n| coach_years6 = 1904\u20131909\n| coach_team6 = [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Cincinnati]]\n| overall_record = 30\u20139 (football) <br>30\u201310 (basketball)\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = Basketball<br>Ohio Collegiate (1908)\n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Amos Parker Foster''' (March 10, 1880 \u2013 August 7, 1952) was an [[American football]] and [[basketball]] player and coach in the early 1900s.  He was a 1904 graduate of [[Dartmouth College]] where he [[Letterman (sports)|lettered]] in both basketball and football.  Foster served as the head football coach at the [[University of Cincinnati]] (1904\u20131905), the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|University of Nebraska]] (1906), and [[Miami University]] (1907\u20131908), compiling a career [[college football]] mark of 30\u20139.  He was also the head basketball coach at Cincinnati for five seasons from 1904 to 1909, tallying a mark of 30\u201310.  After coaching he practiced law in [[Ohio]].<ref name=\"Amos\" />\n\n==Early life==\nFoster was born on March 10, 1880, in [[Keene, New Hampshire]].<ref>{{cite book |title=General Catalogue of Dartmouth College and the Associated Schools 1769-1910 |last=Emerson |first=Charles Franklin |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1911 |publisher=Rumford Press |location=[[Concord, New Hampshire]] |isbn= |page=420 |url=https://archive.org/stream/generalcatalogue00dart#page/420/mode/2up |accessdate=October 31, 2011}}</ref>  He graduated from [[Cushing Academy]] in 1899, where he had played on several athletic teams. He spent the next year doing [[college preparatory]] work at Cushing and was a member of the graduate basketball team, which was named All-New England champion after winning in a tournament of 35 top teams.<ref name=UC>{{cite journal | title =Our New Physical Director | journal = The University of Cincinnati Catalogue 1903-1904| volume = IV | issue = XXXVI | pages = 5 | publisher = The University Press| location = Cincinnati, Ohio | year = 1904| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HrQ4AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA5-IA2&dq=Amos+P.+Foster+cincinnati&cd=6#v=onepage&q=&f=false | issn =  | accessdate = March 8, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nFoster lettered in football in 1902 and 1903 for [[Dartmouth Big Green football|Dartmouth]].  He helped the 1903 team coached by [[Fred Folsom]] to a 9\u20131 record including the school's first-ever win over [[Harvard Crimson football|Harvard]].<ref name=\"Amos\" /><ref>{{cite web|url= http://admin.xosn.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=48870&SPID=4719&DB_OEM_ID=11600&ATCLID=657030|title= 2007 Dartmouth Big Green Football Media Guide}}</ref> Many of the Eastern writers named him to their [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] team for his success his last year at [[Fullback (gridiron football)|fullback]].<ref name=UC />  Foster was also a three-year letter winner for Dartmouth in basketball, lettering in 1901, 1902 and 1903.  During the 1902\u201303 season he served as team captain and led them to a 7\u20139 record.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://dartmouthsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=48790&SPID=4703&DB_OEM_ID=11600&ATCLID=718259|title= 2006-07 Dartmouth Big Green Men's Basketball Media Guide}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nFoster started his coaching career while still at Dartmouth, when he took a job as head basketball coach at the [[Bradford Academy]].  He held this position for two seasons.<ref name=UC />\n\n===Cincinnati===\nFoster was head coach for the [[Cincinnati Bearcats]] in both football and basketball.  He coached the [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati football]] team for two seasons 1904 and 1905.  In his two years as the Bearcat's head coach, he compiled an overall record of 11\u20134.  Foster's most successful year at Cincinnati was in 1904 where he led the Bearcats to a 7\u20131 record.  This team scored 182 points during the season and only gave up 10.  Their seven wins included shutout victories over [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]], [[1904 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]], and traditional rival [[Miami RedHawks football|Miami]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://gobearcats.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/07-media-guide.html|title= 2007 University of Cincinnati Football Media Guide}}</ref> Foster added a 4\u20133 mark in 1905 before taking over the head coaching job at the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|University of Nebraska]] for the 1906 season.<ref name=\"Amos\" /> Foster was also the head coach of the [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|basketball squad at Cincinnati]] from 1904 to 1909. In his five seasons as Bearcats' head coach he compiled an overall record of 30\u201310. His most successful season was in 1908 where he led the Bearcats to a 9\u20130 record and an Ohio Collegiate Championship. Even though Foster left Cincinnati to coach football at other schools, he still coached the Bearcats basketball team.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://gobearcats.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/archive/110706aaa.html|title= 2006-07 University of Cincinnati Basketball Media Guide}}</ref>\n\n===Nebraska===\n[[File:The Charging Machine.jpg|right|thumb|185px|\"The Charging Machine\" introduced by Foster to develop line-men.]]\nFoster replaced [[Walter C. Booth]] as head coach of the [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska football]] team for the 1906 season. He spent just one season as coach of the [[Cornhuskers]], leading them to a 6\u20134 record.<ref name=\" Amos \">{{cite web | url =http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?&DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=920520 | title= Amos Foster \u2013 Husker.com | publisher= University of Nebraska | accessdate= August 11, 2007}}</ref> He was able to beat his former school, Cincinnati, by a score of 41\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=31908&SPID=22&DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=1134395|title= 2007 University of Nebraska Football Media Guide}}</ref>\n\n===Miami===\nFoster was head football coach at [[Miami University]] in [[Oxford, Ohio]], for the 1907 and 1908 seasons. The 1908 team outscored their opponents 113\u201310 and went 7\u20130.  He left Miami with a record of 13\u20131.  His career winning percentage of .939 is the highest in Miami history ahead of [[College Football Hall of Fame]] coaches [[George Little (American football coach)|George Little]], [[Ara Parseghian]], [[Sid Gillman]], [[Woody Hayes]], and [[Bo Schembechler]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://muredhawks.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/05-mediaguide.html|title= 2005 Miami University Football media guide|access-date= August 19, 2006|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071201073006/http://muredhawks.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/05-mediaguide.html|archive-date= December 1, 2007|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n===Football===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1904\n | endyear   = 1905\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1904 college football season|1904]]\n | name         = [[1904 Cincinnati football team|Cincinnati]]\n | overall      = 7\u20131\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1905 college football season|1905]]\n | name         = [[1905 Cincinnati football team|Cincinnati]]\n | overall      = 4\u20133\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Cincinnati\n | overall    = 11\u20134\n | confrecord = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska Cornhuskers]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1906\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1906 college football season|1906]]\n | name         = [[1906 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]]\n | overall      = 6\u20134\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Nebraska\n | overall    = 6\u20134\n | confrecord = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Miami RedHawks football|Miami Redskins]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1907\n | endyear   = 1908\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1907 college football season|1907]]\n | name         = Miami\n | overall      = 6\u20131\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1908 college football season|1908]]\n | name         = [[1908 Miami Redskins football team|Miami]]\n | overall      = 7\u20130\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Miami\n | overall    = 13\u20131\n | confrecord = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 30\u20139\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype = \n | legend   = no\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Find a Grave|160992427}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Cincinnati Bearcats football coach navbox}}\n{{Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Nebraska Cornhuskers football coach navbox}}\n{{Miami RedHawks football coach navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foster, Amos}}\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bearcats football coaches]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth Big Green football players]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth Big Green men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Miami RedHawks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Nebraska Cornhuskers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Ohio lawyers]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Keene, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New Hampshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Amos Foster\n| image = Amos P. Foster.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Foster from 1907 ''Cornhusker''\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1880|3|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Keene, New Hampshire]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1952|8|7|1880|3|10}}\n| death_place = [[Cincinnati|Cincinnati, Ohio]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_sport1 = Football\n| player_years2 = 1902\u20131903\n| player_team2 = [[Dartmouth Big Green football|Dartmouth]]\n| player_sport3 = Basketball\n| player_years4 = 1900\u20131903\n| player_team4 = [[Dartmouth Big Green men's basketball|Dartmouth]]\n| player_positions = [[Fullback (gridiron football)|Fullback]] (football)\n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1904\u20131905\n| coach_team2 = [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n| coach_years3 = 1906\n| coach_team3 = [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]]\n| coach_years4 = 1907\u20131908\n| coach_team4 = [[Miami RedHawks football|Miami (OH)]]\n| coach_sport5 = Basketball\n| coach_years6 = 1904\u20131909\n| coach_team6 = [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Cincinnati]]\n| overall_record = 30\u20139 (football) <br>30\u201310 (basketball)\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = Basketball<br>Ohio Collegiate (1908)\n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Amos Parker Foster''' (March 10, 1880 \u2013 August 7, 1952) was an [[American football]] and [[basketball]] player and coach in the early 1900s.  He was a 1904 graduate of [[Dartmouth College]] where he [[Letterman (sports)|lettered]] in both basketball and football.  Foster served as the head football coach at the [[University of Cincinnati]] (1904\u20131905), the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|University of Nebraska]] (1906), and [[Miami University]] (1907\u20131908), compiling a career [[college football]] mark of 30\u20139.  He was also the head basketball coach at Cincinnati for five seasons from 1904 to 1909, tallying a mark of 30\u201310.  After coaching he practiced law in [[Ohio]].<ref name=\"Amos\" />\n\n==Early life==\nFoster was born on March 10, 1880, in [[Keene, New Hampshire]].<ref>{{cite book |title=General Catalogue of Dartmouth College and the Associated Schools 1769-1910 |last=Emerson |first=Charles Franklin |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1911 |publisher=Rumford Press |location=[[Concord, New Hampshire]] |isbn= |page=420 |url=https://archive.org/stream/generalcatalogue00dart#page/420/mode/2up |accessdate=October 31, 2011}}</ref>  He graduated from [[Cushing Academy]] in 1899, where he had played on several athletic teams. He spent the next year doing [[college preparatory]] work at Cushing and was a member of the graduate basketball team, which was named All-New England champion after winning in a tournament of 35 top teams.<ref name=UC>{{cite journal | title =Our New Physical Director | journal = The University of Cincinnati Catalogue 1903-1904| volume = IV | issue = XXXVI | pages = 5 | publisher = The University Press| location = Cincinnati, Ohio | year = 1904| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HrQ4AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA5-IA2&dq=Amos+P.+Foster+cincinnati&cd=6#v=onepage&q=&f=false | issn =  | accessdate = March 8, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nFoster lettered in football in 1902 and 1903 for [[Dartmouth Big Green football|Dartmouth]].  He helped the 1903 team coached by [[Fred Folsom]] to a 9\u20131 record including the school's first-ever win over [[Harvard Crimson football|Harvard]].<ref name=\"Amos\" /><ref>{{cite web|url= http://admin.xosn.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=48870&SPID=4719&DB_OEM_ID=11600&ATCLID=657030|title= 2007 Dartmouth Big Green Football Media Guide}}</ref> Many of the Eastern writers named him to their [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] team for his success his last year at [[Fullback (gridiron football)|fullback]].<ref name=UC />  Foster was also a three-year letter winner for Dartmouth in basketball, lettering in 1901, 1902 and 1903.  During the 1902\u201303 season he served as team captain and led them to a 7\u20139 record.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://dartmouthsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=48790&SPID=4703&DB_OEM_ID=11600&ATCLID=718259|title= 2006-07 Dartmouth Big Green Men's Basketball Media Guide}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nFoster started his coaching career while still at Dartmouth, when he took a job as head basketball coach at the [[Bradford Academy]].  He held this position for two seasons.<ref name=UC />\n\n===Cincinnati===\nFoster was head coach for the [[Cincinnati Bearcats]] in both football and basketball.  He coached the [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati football]] team for two seasons 1904 and 1905.  In his two years as the Bearcat's head coach, he compiled an overall record of 11\u20134.  Foster's most successful year at Cincinnati was in 1904 where he led the Bearcats to a 7\u20131 record.  This team scored 182 points during the season and only gave up 10.  Their seven wins included shutout victories over [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]], [[1904 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]], and traditional rival [[Miami RedHawks football|Miami]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://gobearcats.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/07-media-guide.html|title= 2007 University of Cincinnati Football Media Guide}}</ref> Foster added a 4\u20133 mark in 1905 before taking over the head coaching job at the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|University of Nebraska]] for the 1906 season.<ref name=\"Amos\" /> Foster was also the head coach of the [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|basketball squad at Cincinnati]] from 1904 to 1909. In his five seasons as Bearcats' head coach he compiled an overall record of 30\u201310. His most successful season was in 1908 where he led the Bearcats to a 9\u20130 record and an Ohio Collegiate Championship. Even though Foster left Cincinnati to coach football at other schools, he still coached the Bearcats basketball team.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://gobearcats.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/archive/110706aaa.html|title= 2006-07 University of Cincinnati Basketball Media Guide}}</ref>\n\n===Nebraska===\n[[File:The Charging Machine.jpg|right|thumb|185px|\"The Charging Machine\" introduced by Foster to develop line-men.]]\nFoster replaced [[Walter C. Booth]] as head coach of the [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska football]] team for the 1906 season. He spent just one season as coach of the [[Cornhuskers]], leading them to a 6\u20134 record.<ref name=\" Amos \">{{cite web | url =http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?&DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=920520 | title= Amos Foster \u2013 Husker.com | publisher= University of Nebraska | accessdate= August 11, 2007}}</ref> He was able to beat his former school, Cincinnati, by a score of 41\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=31908&SPID=22&DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=1134395|title= 2007 University of Nebraska Football Media Guide}}</ref>\n\n===Miami===\nFoster was head football coach at [[Miami University]] in [[Oxford, Ohio]], for the 1907 and 1908 seasons. The 1908 team outscored their opponents 113\u201310 and went 7\u20130.  He left Miami with a record of 13\u20131.  His career winning percentage of .939 is the highest in Miami history ahead of [[College Football Hall of Fame]] coaches [[George Little (American football coach)|George Little]], [[Ara Parseghian]], [[Sid Gillman]], [[Woody Hayes]], and [[Bo Schembechler]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://muredhawks.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/05-mediaguide.html|title= 2005 Miami University Football media guide|access-date= August 19, 2006|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071201073006/http://muredhawks.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/05-mediaguide.html|archive-date= December 1, 2007|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n===Football===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1904\n | endyear   = 1905\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1904 college football season|1904]]\n | name         = [[1904 Cincinnati football team|Cincinnati]]\n | overall      = 7\u20131\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl     